  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong international consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is widely recognized as a serious crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates corruption, and supports organized crime and terrorism.\n\n### Key Points on the Legal Consensus:\n1. **International Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an intergovernmental organization, sets global standards for combating money laundering. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing FATF\u2019s recommendations.\n   \n2. **National Laws**: Nearly every country has enacted laws criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n   - In the United States, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act** establish anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks.\n   - In the European Union, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a comprehensive legal basis for AML efforts.\n\n3. **Criminalization**: Money laundering is explicitly criminalized under international treaties, such as the **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)** and the **United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC)**.\n\n4. **Penalties**: Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and businesses are also required to implement AML measures to detect and report suspicious activities.\n\n5. **Global Cooperation**: Countries cooperate through mechanisms like mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and information-sharing agreements to combat cross-border money laundering.\n\n### Conclusion:\nMoney laundering is universally condemned as illegal, and there is a concerted global effort to prevent, detect, and prosecute it. Governments, financial institutions, and international organizations work together to enforce anti-money laundering laws and maintain the integrity of financial systems.",
